{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868892/1930082101/0238.xml":{"full_text":"Hie Milwaukee Leader\nNorman Thomas is running for congress in a New York dis\ntrict where he does not live. This has again raised discussion as to\nthe propriety of men running for legislative office in places other\nthan their places of residence.\nOf course, the word \u201ccarpetbagger\u201d will be hurled by those who\nfear that he will be elected, but it has no bearing on the case.\nThe practice of running in districts other than that of residence\nis very common in England. Each party has some men whom it is\nvery desirable, from its point of view, to have in the house of com\nmons. If such a man is defeated in one place, he runs again in an\nother place when there is an opportunity^ A by-election affords the\nchance to do this. There is nothing objectionable in the custom.\nIn fact, it is one that might well be emulated in this country more\nthan it has been.\nThe constitution of the United States provides that the house\nof representatives shall be composed of members chosen every sec\nond year by the people of the several states, and that no person\nshall be a representative who shall not have attained the age of 25\nyears, and been seven years a citizen of the United States, and who\nshall not, when elected, be an inhabitant of the state in which he\nshall be chosen.\nThis limits the opportunity to run for congress. A resident of\nWisconsin could not run in Illinois or vice versa. But a resident\nof a given state can run in any district in his own state. In England\none can run anywhere in the country.\nTHE LEAST THAT CAN\nBE DONE\nThe Labor government of England is\nhandicapped in dealing with unemployment\nby the fact that the taxes are already high,\nhence it is hard to raise money for employ\nment projects.\nFinancially, England was harder hit by\nthe war than the United States. We have\nsmall income and inheritance taxes in this\ncountry; they ought to be larger. But in\nEngland they are already pretty high.\nParliament will convene again in the\nfall. Whether anything adequate can be\ndone to provide employment will depend\nmuch on the attitude of the Liberals and\nhow far they are willing to go along with\nthe Labor government. They, are liable to\nbalk at any increase in taxation.\nNevertheless, England has less unem\nployment than the United States. Further\nmore, England pays unemployment insur\nance to the unemployed, and the United\nStates does not.\nThis country ought to adopt unemploy\nment insurance at the very next sessions\nof congress and the state legislatures. If\nthere were a proper amount of concern for\nthe distress of the unemployed and their\nfamilies, congress and the legislatures\nwould be called in special session.\nNot only is this not done, but propa\nganda is made against unemployment in\nsurance so that the bills will have hard\nsledding when the regular sessions come.\nOne of the ways whereby it is sought to\ndiscredit unemployment insurance is by\ncalling it a dole.\nIt is no more a dole than any other in\nsurance. Instead of being a dole, it is a\nright. Certainly in our present compli\ncated and interdependent society, the in\ndustries owe the workers a chance to earn\na living. If they are not given that chance,\nthe least that can be done is to pay them\ninsurance while idle.\nJUDGES ARE HUMAN\nJudging by the way in which witnesses\nhave been grilled by the California supreme\ncourt, the natural inference would be that\nthe court is hostile to Mooney and Billings\nand wants to discredit their witnesses if\npossible.\nJudges are like other men. They have\ntheir dislikes and their prejudices. Some\npeople think that when a man ascends the\nbench he leaves these human qualities and\nfrailties behind and becomes a superman\nwith a \u201cjudicial temperament\u201d which en\nables him to decide cases purely on the law.\nThat notion is the bunk. The sooner the\npeople find it out, the better. There would\nbe no \u201cgovernment by injunction\u201d if judges\nwere not prejudiced. There would be no\ndecisions against the public welfare. It is\nnecessary that the false glamor should be\nstripped away from judges and courts.\nThis paper has been engaged in doing so\nfor, 10, these many years.\nMany judges are foxy enough not to\nshow their prejudices, but carry them into\ntheir decisions just the same. That makes\nthem all the more dangerous.\nOf course this is not saying that there\nare no high-minded judges who try to be\nfair and square in cases involving the pub\nlic welfare. But all too many of them are\nguided in such matters by the bias which\nthey gained through Iheir associations be\nfore going on the bench.\nNo Objection\nEDITORS\u2019\nWhat Do You\nThink About It?\nFROM HAWAII.\nTo the Editor:\nThe Leader evokes memories of\n12 years ago when it was to me a\nfamiliar newspaper in Kenosha,\nwhere my parents still live.\nTwelve years ago\u2014Waukegan\nto Sheboygan was a familiar\nstamping route of mine /in those\ndays. Trying to organize the\nLake Shore Circle of the Y. P.\nS. L.\u2014a branch in every lake\nshore city\u2014was a pleasant ex\nperience. Then, the Lithuanian\nbranch of the Socialist party and\nthe county central committee\u2014\nboth of Kenosha \u2014once engaged\nmost of my spare time. Later\ncame years of vagabonding\u2014of\ndreaming.\nToday I am employed as cus\ntodian of the University of Ha\nwaii gymnasium. I\u2019m doing a\ncolumn of subdued cynicism and\nwise-cracking on the side for a\nHonolulu weekly and free-lanc\ning in general. In addition, I\u2019m\nhaving built a 3G-foot cruising\nyawl, in which the wife and I\nplan to eke out a living on a pro\nlonged vagabonding cruise around\nthe world. We expect to start\nlate in 1931.\nConditions here are as bad as\non the mainland. We who have\njobs hang on to them. Those who\nare out of work are out of luck.\nThe big interests control every\nthing\u2014a trite expression that,\nfor it is true the country over.\nThe local press doesn\u2019t print a\n10th of what you do. Sugar is\nking. Pineapples come second.\nThe tourist crop is harvested an\nnually and those who are in the\nmoney are congenitally Pollyan\nnish. The rest of us are just job\nholders.\nI\u2019ll bid you a comradely\n\u201cAloha.\u201d\nFRED E. TRUMAN.\nHonolulu, Hawaii.\nTHE COURTS.\nTo the Editor:\nWhy was Judge Stolen rein\nstated and Ray Cannon\u2019s applica\ntion denied? Was it because he\nhad courage enough to run\nagainst Judge Fowler?\nI should also like to know why\nthere is such little criticism di\nrected against our supreme court.\nIf an aiderman, or our mayor,\nor a justice of peace does any\nthing that may be wrong the pa\npers all criticise them, but our su\npreme court can decide cases day\nafter day for the big corporations\nagainst the poor people and not\na word is said about it in the pa\npers.\nIt is about time at least some\nof our papers were waking up and\ngiving the people the facts as to\nwhat is going on. You cannot ex\npect The Milwaukee Journal, or\nThe Milwaukee Sentinel to give\nthe public the truth concerning de\ncisions handed down by our su\npreme court. We do, however, de\npend upon The Milwaukee Lead\ner. So let\u2019s have the truth from\nhere on I\nThe laboring people are going\nto watch these judges from now\non. HARRY L. M\u2019KAY.\nCONTAMINATED.\nTo the Editor:\nI see by the paper that Norman\nThomas had a debate with mod\nern capitalism. I quite agree\nwith Mr. Insull that Socialism is\nslavery because I think that ev\nerybody is a slave to his or her\nsurroundings to some extent, but\nunder the dog eat dog system of\ncompetition vast numbers of peo\nple are slaves to a few people but\nunder Socialism people would be\neach other\u2019s slaves like washing\neach other\u2019s feet.\nThe system of private property\nor capitalism is likened to a man\nwho eats and drinks certain so\ncalled foods that are foreign to\nthe body, and the body becomes\nso contaminated with broken\ndown tissue that the man becomes\nsick in bed. Can't eat. Nature\nforces him to fast, result de\npression. That seems to me to be\nour economic condition today.\nEBER WRIGHT.\nGladwin, Mich.\nSOME FACTS YOU SHOULD\nKNOW\nWhen you are sick the first step you should\ntake toward getting well is to find out the cause\nof your ailment. Business in America in sick.\nHere is a plain statement of the cause.\nThese are days when almost everybody is talk\ning about hard times, poor business, unemployment\nand the desperate struggle which millions are hav\ning in order to live.\nBut while people talk and wonder what the\nmatter can be with the country, how many persons\nactually know the cause of hard times and business\ndepression? Very few, I think. Most people have\nno knowledge of economic laws and therefore all\nthey can do is to \u201cwonder what is the matter.\u201d\nBut if we >are wise we will dig down and try to\nfind out the cause of the evil conditions which\nafflict us so that in time we may apply a remedy\nif there is one.\nNow, why should millions of men be unable to\n\u201cget work\u201d when their families are suffering for\nthe necessities of life and the factories in which\nthese necessities can be produced are standing\nclosed? Why cannot this great army of unem\nployed go into the idle mills, mines, land and fac\ntories and produce with their own labor the neces\nsities of life which they require?\nThe answer is plain: They do not own the fac\ntories and they have no right to work there\u2014nor\nanywhere. Now here we have struck the trail of\nthe first cause of unemployment. Our society is\norganized upon the basis of private ownership.\nAll the great industries are privately owned and\noperated with the single purpose of making profits\nfor the private owners. Profit is the first incen\ntive of ownership and is the final and only goal\nof these owners. Very well, then, how are these\nprofits to be made?\nFirst, labor must be employed, but this labor\ncannot be paid the full value of its product, be\ncause in that case there would be no profit for\nthe owner. So, in return for the goods which it\nproduces labor is given what the employer calls\n\u201cwages,\u201d and which represents only a fraction, from\none-fifth to one-half, of the actual wealth which\nlabor has created. The balance of labor\u2019s product\nis taken by the employer and is called profit.\nNow, on Saturday night if the worker goes out\nand spends every penny of his earnings he is only\nable to buy goods equal in value to a portion of\nthe goods which his labor has produced. And when\nthe entire working class goes out and spends every\ndollar it has received in wages, it is still unable\nto buy back but a portion of the goods its labor\nhas produced. The remainder stays in the hands\nof the employing or owning class and represents\ntheir \u201cprofit.\u201d\nIf the foreign market is not sufficient to absorb\nthis surplus or \u201cprofit\u201d it accumulates in the hands\nof the owners. They cannot sell it to the working\nclass because the workers have spent all their earn\nings in purchasing only a portion of the product.\nIt is useless for employers to manufacture more\ngoods when they cannot dispose of those they have\non hand\u2014and so the factory is closed down, and\nthus comes unemployment, hard times, want and\nsuffering. This condition is repeated every few\nyears and must continue and grow worse as long\nas the present profit system lasts. It cannot be\ndenied or excused or explained away.\nThe remedy is to give the workers access to the\nmeans of production through public ownership\u2014\nthat would secure them in the right to produce\ntheir necessities regardless of some capitalist\u2019s\nprofits. It would secure them the right to own\nall they produced. If they produced more than they\ncould consume they could reduce the hours cf labor\nand could live in comfort and enjoyment instead\nof suffering for the surplus locked in the ware\nhouses of their masters, as they do today.\nThus the bitter, heartless struggle for existence\nwould disappear: crime and most evils which afflict\nhuman society would, in a large mor sure, vanish.\nA new civilization would be born.\nTo effect these results it is only necessary that\nthe great industrial enterprises be collectively in\nstead of privately owned\u2014that they be operated for\nthe benefit of the working class, Instead of the\nprofit of private owners.\nAnd this is Socialism.\u2014Humanity.\nUNEMPLOYMENT\nDEMONSTRATED\nFor the past six months the question of unem\nployment has been discussed from various angles\nby representatives in Washington. A number of\nbills have been introduced to relieve the unem\nployed. One of these aimed to determine whether\nor not there was such a thing as unemployment and\nthe extent of it.\nThis demand for exact information has been met\nby a demonstration in Washington. The United\nStates civil service commission announced that it\nwould receive applications on July 30 for 200 scrub\nwomen at S9O a month. At 8 o\u2019clock on the night\nof July 29 a line of applicants started to form out\nside the commission\u2019s office, less than two blocks\nfrom the white house. Over 1,000 persons made\napplications for the 200 jobs available and thou\nsands of others were turned away. It is Indefinite\nwhen the successful applicants will get their jobs.\nThis demonstration ought to satisfy all doubts\nin the minds of the president and congress regard\ning the magnitude of the unemployment problem.\nMinnesota Union Advocate.\nThe Milwauke Leader\nPublished tn Milwaukee. Wls.. every afternoon ex\n\u00abPt S^dav_ EDITORIAL AND PUBLICATION\nm \u201d28-32 Juneau Avenue at Sixth Street\nTelephone: Marquette 7500.\nE. J. COSTELLO Editor.\nAssociate Editor John M Work: Managing Editor.\nLeo Wolfsohn: City Editor. Frank Haggerty: Snorts\nEditor Ben Smith: Advertising Manager Elmer A\nKrahn\n01388 matter August 25, 1920, at the\noostofnce at Milwaukee. Wia. under the act oi March 3. 1879\nSUBSCRIPTION RaTES\u2014Mail editions tn United\nStates: Three months $1.50: six months. $3: one\nvear $6. To foreign countries: Three months $3:\n*dx months. $6: one vear sl2\nThe home edition is delivered by carriers in Mil\nwaukee and county for 15 cents a week or 65 cents a\nmonth: elsewhere bv carrier 18 cents a week or 80\n^ents a month.\nADVERIISI^IG subject to publisher's acceptance\nRates on application FOREIGN ADVERTISING\nREPRESENTATIVES: Fralfck. Bates Alward. inc\nNew York: 270 Madison Avenue. Room 1301. Chicago:\n605 North Michigan Avenue. San Francisco and Los\nAngeles.\n^TRAPES COUNOL^\nBottle-Time\n3# ^^z)/ i <^L\\3\nDOESN\u2019T SEE WHY FAMILY AL- A 5 A MATTER OF FACT MILK HE'D MUCH RATHER PLAY\nWAYS TAKES IT FOR GRANTED 15 TAE LAST THING HE WANTS WITH W 5 BK6E\u00bb\u00bb\nTHAT HE'S SLAP TO GET Hls RIGHT NOU/. HE'S SKK AND\nBOTTLE TiRED OF IT\nOH PEAR, THE FAMILY HAS THIS SORT OF MAKES AIM NOW PADP^ LOOKING VERY\nDISCOVERED HE'S NOT TAKING MAP MOTHER'S HOLDING STERN SAVS HE'LL MAKE\nHIS BOTTLE, AND HAS START' TAE BOTTLE IN His MOUTH. HIM PRINK HIS MILK ALLR/GHT\nED K> TUSS WELL. HE WO^T DRINK\nGw\nAFTER HOLDING IT FOR TEN PARENTS GIVE UP, WITH A GOOD DECIDES HE'S HUNGRY\nMINUTES DADDY TAKES A DEAL OF SIGHING THAT IT ISN\u2019T NOW, ANYWAY\nREADING AND FINDS NOT NATURAL AND OUGHT THEY CALL\nAN OUNCE HAS GONS\u2019 THE DOCTOR, RlNp OF PATHETC-PARENT\n(Copyright, 1930, by The Bell Syndicate. Inc.) 6*Zl\nParliament has closed down for\nthe recess after the longest ses\nsion since the war came to an end.\nThere is not one member, left wing\nor right wing, who does not sigh\nwith relief at the prospect of a\nfew weeks\u2019 respite from the nerve\nwrecking experiences they have\nhad to undergo. It would be idle\nto suggest that everyone is quite\nsatisfied with the progress made,\nand yet, this final week saw the\nroyal assent given to several very\nimportant measures which now\nbecomes Acts of Parliament.\nAlarums and excursions, conges\ntion of business, last minute rush,\nwere a feature of the last days.\nA packed house listened to the\ncharges of bribery and corruption\nand break of privilege as the re\nsult of Sandham\u2019s sensational\nstatements the previous week and\nto which I referred in my last\nnotes. Then empty benches to lis\nten to the debate on Egypt and\nthe safety of the lives of Euro\npeans and the Suez canal.\nAgain the house filled up to\nhear the solemn censure passed\nupon Sandham by the speaker,\nand this was followed by discus\nsions on India and Irak with\nhardly a dozen members in at\ntendance. Indeed it would appear\nthat the members of parliament\nwere far more interested in scan\ndal concerning themselves than in\nfundamentals.\nSandham seemed to be genuine\nly surprised to learn that he had\ncommitted a breach of privilege.\nUe is quite new to parliamentary\nlife, having only entered the house\nat the last general election, al\nthough he has been one of the\nmost active Socialist propagan\ndists for years. His absence from\nthe house on the day when, ac\ncording to rule the matter was\nfirst raised, and his evidence be\nfore the committee of privileges\nshows that. It was also clear that\nthe house would have preferred a\njudicial inquiry -to the allega\ntions, and there was no attempt\nby the committee, composed as it\nis of members from all parties, to\nsmother such an inquiry.\nThe real trouble is that what\never accusations may be brought\nagainst members outside the\nhouse, whether an M. P. or not,\nno judicial committee could be set\nup to cross-examine every mem\nber of a party in the endeavor to\nfind the guilty people. If, on the\nother hand, specific names are\nmentioned, then a judicial inquiry,\nif there is prima facie evidence,\nmust test the allegations. If\nSandham had given even one\nname, it would have been enough.\nDespite Snowden\u2019s offer to set up\nsuch a tribunal, no name, no ac\ncusation was definitely forthcom\ning, and there the matter rests for\nthe moment.\nMost members are very uneasy\nabout these vague charges hang\ning over their heads. There is a\ngeneral feeling that even now\nthere ought to be an inquiry of\nsome sort.\n\nThe very congestion of the time\ntable and the inevitable com\nplaints from the house of lords\nthat they have had far too much\nwork thrust upon them by the\nLabor government at the last mo\nment is an indication of how\nmuch has been actually accom\nplished in the past session. Once\nmore the upper house tried to dic\ntate to commons, this time over\nthe transport bill. Although orig\ninally a Tory measure and de\nsigned to be strictly non-party, it\nhas been altered almost out of\nrecognition since it passed the\nhouse of lords, where it originated,\nand is now a measure of first\nclass importance.\nIt is something new, for exam\nple, to insist upon fair working\nconditions and reasonable wages\nfor a great industry like road\ntransport by act of parliament.\nThis clause raised the ire of the\nlords and they attempted to strike\nit out. The government stuck to\ntheir guns, however, and fearful\nof what might he the result of\nsuch open defiance, the lords gave\nway.\n\nThere was a good deal of cheap\ntalk about the insult to Sir John\nSECTION\nBY JESSIE STEPHEN.\nLETTER FROM LONDON\nSimon because the government re\nfuses to have him on the delega\ntion at the round table confer\nence on India. They intend to\nuse his services in a consultative\ncapacity but in no other way.\nThe strongest reason against\nhis appointment, as a nominee of\nthe Liberal party was the fact\nthat certain groups in India\nwould refuse to send delegates if\nthe chairman of the Indian com\nmission Iwas to sit with them. I\nrather \u2019fancy Lloyd George and\nSir Austen Chamberlain spoke\nwith their tongues in their cheeks.\nSimon himself eased the situation\nby saying definitely he did not\ndesire to make mischief and would\nmuch rather his appointment was\nnot pressed.\n\nA dramatic gesture by the La\nbor government in connection\nwith the insurance of two ships\nto be built by the Cunard Co. has\nbrought joy to the hearts of thou\nsands of unemployed shipyard\nworkers.\nFor some time these ships, or\nrather the building of them, has\nbeen held up because no insurance\ncompany cared to insure these\nmammoth vessel^ which are to\ncost $60,000,000 to build. Now the\ngovernment has stepped In and\ntaken the risk which the ordinary\ncapitalist insurance companies\nwould not assume. Work will thus\nproceed immediately, and the\nClydeside which has been so bad\nly hit by the past war slump will\nbenefit and will get the first ship.\nThe other one is to be built on\nthe Tyne where work has been\nscarce for years. Not less than\n20,000 men will find employment\nfor two and a half years, and to\nthose who know the areas affected\nit is obvious that the reactions on\nBritish industry of these vast con\ntracts will be enormous.\nThe areas I have mentioned\nhave suffered cruelly and there\nwas great joy when the good\nnews was broadcast.\nSnowden, deputizing for the\nprime minister who had gone on\nholiday the day before, closed the\nsession with a promise of definite\naction in the agricultural indus\ntry when the new session begins.\nHe foreshadowed a great increase\nin home-produced food supplies\nand a return of prosperity to the\ncountryside. The program com\nprises proposals to make land more\nfreely available for small cultiva\ntors; create a special class of al\nlotments and market gardens, and\npoultry holdings up to five acres\nfor suitable unemployed workers.\nThere is to be an Agricultural\nLand Cultivation corporation to\nconduct large scale farming and\ndemonstration farms; reorganize\nmarketing on the lines laid down\nin the agricultural marketing bill,\nwhich I shall explain in a mo\nment discuss the establishment of\nWONDERS ot thi WORLD\nCAVE LIFE.\nCaves are used as retreats by\nsome animals, during times of in\nclement weather or during times\nof danger. Others use them as\nhotels for over night. Some enter\nby accident and, finding the dark\nness pleasant and the shelter\nfrom heat and cold comfortable,\nremain for a time. Some use\ncaves only for breeding places.\nBut many spiders, salamanders,\ncrickets, flies and beetles live per\nmanently in caves, and gradually\nlose the use of their eyes.\nCaves remain cool and moist in\nsummer, when all the surround\ning country is hot and dry, and\nin winter they offer shelter from\nthe icy blasts outside. On the\nwhole the temperature of deep\ncaves changes very little.\nThe most populous caves are\nthose where there is considerable\nmoisture. Many animals live in\nthe darkest parts o F these caves,\nnever even approaching the mouth\nwhere light streams in. Their\nfood is generally the waste prod\nucts left in the cave by animals\nBY GLUYAS WILLIAMS\nimport boards and the dominions;\nprovide improved rural housing.\nThe marketing bill outlined by\nthe chancellor of the exchequer\nin his statement to the house pro\nposes the establishment of mar\nketing boards for various prod\nucts, to be elected by the produc\ners themselves, and the market\ning scheme drawn up by any\nboard will be binding on all pro\nducers of the product concerned in\nthe area which the board covers.\nThis may be the whole country,\nI or only a part, just as common\nsense and the exigencies of the\nindustry dictate.\nIndividual producers and the\nconsumers are protected by re\nquiring the minister of agricul\nture, before approving a scheme,\nto give notice of it, to consider\nany representations made, and to\ngive parliament the opportunity of\nvetoing it. The interests of the\npublic are further nrntocted by\nthe setting up of a special \u201ccon\nsumers\u2019 committee\u201d for every\nscheme, and the bill also contains\nprovision for the establishment\nof a committee of investigation to\nwhich the minister may refer\ncomplaints. There is also some\ntalk of including something to en\ncourage agricultural research and\neducation, ^nd also a proposal to\nmake advances to producers where\nnecessary. This financial assist\nance will be by way of going and\nshort term loans, available for the\nmarketing boards.\n\nOnce these measures are\npassed, it should not be very long\nbefore the results of scientific\nmarketing of home produce proves\nto be beneficial both to growers\nand consumers. At present both\nthese are fleeced by the middle\nmen. At the present time we im\nport $100,000,000 worth of eggs\neach year, and there is no reason\nin the world why we should not\nproduce them all at home. It\ncould be done if we can sell them\nas economically as the Danish\npeople do, but this presupposes the\nindustry shall be run with the\nsame scientific accuracy.\nMillions of acres of corn land\nhave gone out of cultivation alto\ngether during the last few years.\nIn the last 12 months no less than\n140,000 acres has ceased to pro\nduce corn. If the marketing\nscheme can help here, it will mean\ndefinitely, a reduction in the cost\nof living and a great increase in\nemployment for those normally en\ngaged in agricultural work.\n\nGood work was done in Labor\u2019s\nfirst lap. Next session we hope\nto reap the reward of sound plan\nning, and I do not think we shall\nbe disappointed. Indeed, one Lib\neral member declared the govern\nment had done so well, despite the\ncriticisms of its dilatoriness and\nineptitude, he saw no reason why\nw T ho go out for their food and the\nanimal and plant stuff washed in\nby streams, or the fungi growing\niri\nI H x\nv 1\n1 r 1\n'7\n\non the dank floor and walls of\nthe. cave\nThese cave dwellers, living for\never in the same darkness, have\nno seasons for. breeding and hi-\nThursday, August 21, 1930\nSplinters\nAdd to obsolete sayings:\n\u201cFill\u2019er up.\u201d\nA man doesn\u2019t really sigh for\nthe good old days. He just sighs\nfor a lost appetite.\nA he-man. daughter, is one\nwho despises the movie hero who\nseems the ideal he-man to you.\nThe worst feature about that\nbaby mix-up in Chicago is its\nprobable effect on movie produc\ners.\nMaybe the art of conversation\njust seems to have disappeared\nbecause it Is called bridge now.\nThere\u2019s just as much money In\nhard times. There\u2019s just as\nmuch blood in a dead man\u2014but\nit isn\u2019t circulating.\nChief Justice Wheat rules that\nminiature golf isn\u2019t golf. It\u2019s\njust- puttering around.\nFrance and Italy are willing\nto bury the hatchet. You can\ntell by the way they look at one\nanother\u2019s necks.\nAmericanism: Painting soft\npine to imitate oak; trying to\nachieve culture by the same\nmethod.\nPublicity is what enables\nclimbers to reach the top. Look\nwhat it has done for thermome\nters lately.\nYou can tell a Chinese army\nthat is inspired by \u201cReds.\u201d The\nprivates grab part of the loot in\nstead of giving the general all of\nit.\nOne reason why people don\u2019t\nbuy stocks while they\u2019re cheap is\nbecause shoestrings don\u2019t grow\nwithout the help of imagination.\nJi\nAmbition is the quality that\nkeeps dad from spanking Willie\nfor throwing rocks at passing\nderbies provided he always hits\nthem.\nWe had almost got out of the\nhabit of feeling sorry for Ru\nmania and then King Carol ap\npeared in the talkies.\nFord says only one family in\n10 has a bath tub, but maybe\nthey merely look that way on\nSunday morning because they\naren\u2019t going to church.\nThe strange part of it Is that\ntourists who steal the farmer\u2019s\nflowers feel superior to people\nwho steal money.\nThere must have been some\nkind of law enforcement problem\nin Greece. Old Diogenes searched\nin vain for an honest man.\nCorrect this sentence: \u201cWhen\nI Whs your age,\u201d said dad, \u201cI felt\nvery grateful for the kindness of\nmy parents.\u201d\nThe Imposter\nA conceited old boy who was\nsingle\nWith the opposite sex tried to\nmingle;\nBut they hooted him out\nWith laughter and shout\nWhen they found \u2019twas his keys\nmade the jingle.\nHow Many?\nAlgernon (reading joke)\nFancy\u201d this, Percy: A chap thinks\nthat a football com-h has four\nwheels.\nPercy\u2014Haw. haw! And how\nmany wheels has the bally thing?\nFound He Wasn\u2019t\n\u201cI\u2019m surprised to hear you are\nmoving back to the city. I thought\nyou were a farmer.\u201d\n\u201cYes! I thought so too.\u201d\nit should not last another three\nyears. Neither do I, but merit\ndoes not always count in politics.\nbernating and feeding as do the\ncreatures subject to the winter\ncold and summer heat outside.\nEven the permanent residents\nonce lived outside. Some of these\nare more recent comers than oth\ners and they sometimes retain the\nhabits of their former life for a\ntime. Rut since they cannot tell\nthe difference between day and\nnight in the black depths of the\ncaves where they have learned to\nlive, they soon forgot that their\nancestors slept through the night\nand were awake and busy through\nthe day, or the other way about.\nCertain bats are said to live in\ncaves about five-sixths of their\nlives Moths and mosquitoes live\nin caves during the winter and\nmany flies and beetles breed in\noaves. Most of the permanent\ncave dwellers are blind.\nDifferent kinds of animals\nfound in caves show different de\ngrees of adjustment to cave life.\nSome scientists believe that ani\nmals in caves are those whose an\ncestors found life outside too dif\nficult.\nNext\u2014Look at His Teeth.\n(Copyright, 1930, oy Republic HyWI-\nI cate, lac.J","height":"28941","width":"21666"}}
